Fantastic port. The onscreen control pad character movement is very fluid. The interface and menu system is a breeze. I spent untold hours back in the day playing this on PC. I, like many others was holding off from this purchase because it doesnt include the expansions. Boy was I wrong. I have to say, this game on my 10" tablet is almost jaw dropping. Ok, I ripped myself away long enough to write this review, now back to the game.

Love the game on PC, now works great on my tablet too. I would rate it 5 stars but the developers set it up for On Screen joystick Controls only. No tap to move or tap enemy to attack (you know, basic touch screen operations), and no basic gamepad support which is easily implimented in most game development engines. Lack of foresight for such a simple implementation is a no-no in my book.

This isn't a port of TQAE, it's a port of TQ vanilla straight from 2006. In some ways, I get it. The old TQ was probably much smaller and less graphics intensive, perfect for mobile. But apart from the interface, they made basically no changes to it. Given that there have been so many improvements to the playability in the last 14 years it is unforgivable not to have potion stacking, caravans or inventory sorting. These aren't even big changes, they were in the original. Step backwards.

The biggest issue is that the game is simply not fun. Removing the need to click on an enemy and having an autolock feature for ranged combat means that a mage or ranged run is extremely repetitive and boring. You walk a few yards, hold down attack button, collect repetitive loot. Do this 300 more times. Setting and tone also don't 'pop'. I don't get lost in the setting or the mystique of the player character. I never played the original TQ, but this is not anywhere near a great game.

Tldr; Poor port, bland gameplay, avoid. This is the basic version of Titan Quest - no relics, poor itemisation etc. This port is very poor, controls are frustrating, your character gets stuck and stops responding few times every minute, auto target is infuriating. Maps are massive and feature zero secrets, zero hidden areas, zero rewards and very little monsters. Levelling is tedious and boring. Past level 10 you'll take well over an hour to gain a level. Game lags and has flickering and bugs.

Clunky, unresponsive controls! I would love to enjoy this game, but it is impossible with not properly working controls. Very often following happens when attack button is pressed: 1) Instead of attacking, hero decides to run to the right direction even though attack button doesn't control movement directly. It is very frustrating during the battle. 2) Nothing happens at all. Hero decides not to attack and stand still. Sometimes in the heat of the battle you don't even notice that your hero is just standing and chilling which usually results in death. Additional problems: 3) Very often movement control doesn't work either. You try to move in any direction, but your hero decides to wait a bit or doesn't move at all. 4) Active skills are very unresponsive during the battle. You need to mash these buttons several times for them to be registered - very frustrating. Please fix these bugs. EDIT: While problems remain, I am positively impressed by devs support and responses through email. This is a behavior of a good and fair company, so I am changing my rating.

3 stars for me. For years this was one of the best top-down RPG (Diablo-like) game there was on Android and it still may be to this day. The mechanics are solid and it's a great port from the original (I think) PC version but ports and revamps have it's issues and this has a few of them. The GAMEPLAY is okay, but the wonky frame rate makes making precise movements an issue sometimes. The GRAPHICS are awesome for an android port (pretty much looks like the PC version) but when you zoom out really far, it might be a little harder to see some enemies like skeletons. Maybe it's because of the small screen?  The lack of cloud saves is too bad especially for someone like me who's like switch playing it from on different devices. The weird CONTROLS is a downer since it's pretty awkward keeping your thumb on one part of the screen. An option to change the UI size and positioning would've been nice. Also, an optional tap-to-move would be very welcome. Certain commands or settings from pets were missing, just to add. Overall, this is an okay purchase. If you're looking for a decent game on Android that isn't a cash-grabbing MMO, this is a good solo only game.
Blizzard: take notes. This is how you make a Diablo-like game on mobile.

First off, this game is awesome. I never originally played the PC version but have since picked it up for PC, and it was actually one of the main reasons I bought my Nintendo Switch. The PC version is great but I mostly play this on the go, so the mobile version is my preference. Although I have a bunch of other games now, I mostly got a Switch so I could get the expansions and DLC on the go since I've played the original content on the mobile app to death. As crazy as that sounds, yes I bought a $300 mobile console so I could play more Titan Quest content. I mention this because even still, I much more prefer the phone version and I'm hoping the developer or whoever owns the rights now plan to release an update or new app with the expansions and DLC. I think most of the reviews pretty much agree, people are certainly willing to pay for it! Anyway, great game so pick it up and check it out if you haven't. Easily worth the price.. tons of content already, nearly limitless replayability, lots of choices of both classes, skill trees and equipment to suit any play style. I have logged over 300 hours on the mobile version and other than craving more content I have nothing bad to say about it. There are a couple glitches here and there, mostly visual and not game breaking or even game impacting. I've run into a few issues with my character saves, but full disclosure it's strictly because I was modding and has never happened otherwise. Couple important points which are probably already stated somewhere: this is the original TQ without any of the expansions. There is no caravan storage, no artifacts, no arcane formulas, no Dream class, and only 3 acts. Once you beat Typhon it's game over and you unlock the next difficulty. It also appears that this is prior to any fan patches (which I think was for Immortal Throne anyway) so some things fixed there still appear to be broken (i.e. debuffs from some Spirit skills, etc.) Although I haven't done extensive testing on that so I may easily be wrong. Anyway great game.. I'd say would buy again, but already did buy again on iOS, PC and Nintendo Switch.

The battery drain has been fixed and I can now play this for hours on my train commute. This game is absolutely not worth the price tag. Don't get me wrong, this 
is a fantastic port. A few of the decisions DotEmu made in the shift really 
make playing this game on mobile a lot of fun. I actually found I prefer 
the controls in mobile to PC. Depite this, I cannot rate the game higher 
than two stars. There are two very specific reasons for this: - The 
auto-targeting system is fantastic for melee, but makes ranged play almost 
impossible. - There is a game breaking bug in the movement control that 
will randomly and often lock a character in place. These two points make 
Conqueror the only playable class. If these issues were addressed, you'd be 
looking at the best game available for android.

I understand that this is an emulator, essentially turning your controls from mouse & keyboard, to touch screen. It does any play job, but there's clear limitations. Rapid touches from movement to attacking, usually end up having you run directly into combat. Opening a chest as enemies approach, can be a mistake, as your attack turns to pickup item, and remains that way until you lift your finger...which, under heavy combat can often have you just standing there. I think the shortcoming is bad implementation of the click mechanism and the auto pickup drops, coupled with the attack turn to pickup...if that makes sense.   Also, autosave has screwed me, as I saved up a lot of points, because this was my first play through. Unsure of the direction I wanted to take...I regretfully invested my points in maxing the hunter mastery....and it can't be undone. **you can prevent the game from autosaving, by pressing the home key and force closing the app...DO NOT EXIT TO THE MENUS IN GAME

It is titan quest! It really is. I sank so much of my life into the pc version. It is weird to be excited for a game all over again 11 years later.   Controls are surprisingly great. With in 15 minutes of play it feels quite natural.  One suggestion. Add a body decay function? This will help keep frame rates high.  It is how ever not with out its flaws. No multiplayer. Which is understandable. The storage guy seems to be gone. One of the big draws for me was picking up an awesome item for another class. Immediately starting a character so i could play with that item.  Meaning play through one usually makes me want to start play through 2 as soon as i can. No storage guy. No item trading.  If you are looking for a great meaty experience you cant go wrong with this port of a great game. Buy it. You wont regret it.

BEWARE: If you sunk hours into the PC version, read this before you cash in your hard-earned digital coin.  There's no stash? How can there not be a stash? That is a BASIC requirement for the genre, and it certainly was included in the original. That cost this review 1 star  The controls for Eternium: Mages and Minions  would make this game. As it is, you basically can't use charge skills, and after realizing how bad they were I read around that most skills behave the same way. The controls are basically broken. That cost this review about 2 stars.  How on earth can you guys charge so much for an unfinished game? Why on earth don't you spend some time updating it to improve the end-user experience?

It's the full classic game, with a control scheme that is basically unplayable. This is a Diablo clone, click to move, click to attack, etc., the perfect game to port to touchscreen. Why on earth would you make a virtual dpad and context based action button? The dpad works as well as any others, so not very. The action button changes context by what you're near, so you'll spend a lot of time getting swarmed by enemies while your character derps around picking up useless items. Ability buttons are so small you may as well not bother trying use them. Only positive is that it is a full game with no ads or iap, so it gets 2 stars instead of 1.

Great potential troubled by poor framerate (Nexus 6P) and clunky controls. The context sensitive button used to attack changes to grab items when you're close to one, effectively taking you out of combat and running your character around.   Performance is the biggest issue, with constant low framerate affecting touch inputs.
I put skill points in some skills but I am unable to use them as they do not appear in the skill bar.

The game  is worth the purchase although there's this bug that if you hold the attack button, the character keeps running towards the enemy and continues the same direction without stop. I find that tapping attack works better and fixes that. Also, there are times when I cannot move even when I am already holding or tapping repeatedly the joystick. It's very difficult to escape at grave times when it occurs. Hopefully these movement bugs will be fixed and the control interface will be much easier like targeting with a bow or spell.

Those who have problems with low framrate can change the resolution in battery saver or game launcher settings . some cases it would still have a scaling issue then go to android folder and preferences folder and delete the settings folder . next time the game launches at lower resolution it will create a new settings file with lower resolution and fps is solved .

replyContent:
Hello,

This is a Google Play Store issue that happens at the first start up of an app. Please uninstall the game, clear the Google Play Services cache files from your device and reinstall the game from a stable internet connection.

If the issue is still present, please send an email to support@dotemu.com.

Thank you for your understanding.

replyContent:
Hello and thank you very much for your message.

This is a known issue that appears randomly. There is a fix for it, but it requires some precise manipulations. Please send an email to support@dotemu.com so that we can help you fix it.

We are deeply sorry for the inconvenience and we thank you for your understanding.

I love Titan quest and am rather happy that I can play it on mobile but the controls suffer here and it can make gameplay a chore. If the developer reads this I would recommend that you do away with the action button and joystick control and go to a more traditional tap to move and attack control set. I would also recommend that you can toggle loot selection so that you don't try to pick it up during a fight. Other than that the game runs well and looks great but I am hesitant to recommend it due to the controls.   edit: I did a derp. The game does have a toggle switch so that you don't pick up items in combat. It makes the controls far more user friendly.

I've had to take 2 stars off for abysmal controls (you cannot even select you own target - in a hack and slash, really? - the auto targeting doesn't work well at all, and as someone else said, unless you quickly switch it off, your toon will try to pick up loot while being pounded on). I never played the PC version, so I cannot compare the two. I can only report what I've found. I have to rate the game for Android and, it has the potential to be up there with the Baldur's Gate series, Bard's Tale, and KotOR (all of which I love on Android, but also never played the PC versions - yea, I missed out on some good titles), if they'd fix a few simple problems. Sometimes, too, the character doesn't fight until you move a little first (I've died a couple times because of this, until I discovered I had to take a step or two to re-enable attacks). Overall, I almost recommend the game (except for the controls), especially if you're an RPG fan. Runs OK on my Samsung Galaxy TabPRO SM-T900 12.2" with Android 5.1.1.

As for gameplay smoothness, tried it with both Huawei P9 Plus and Samsung Galaxy Tab S2 and didn't suffer any problems.  To all you whiners, it's not the game, it's your outdated device. Go play something less graphic intensive like Angry Bird. Update: Couldn't teleport back to my last location as the option wasn't there. For anyone having an issue with the resolution, go to Data>titanquest>files>preferences>settings> and edit the options.txt file. The line that says resolution, add an "x" between the resolution length and width. That should fix the problem the next time you start up Titan Quest.

replyContent:
Hello,

This is a known issue and we are investigating it, but we haven't been able to reproduce it yet. 

In order to correct this issue, please remove the following folder from your device: "/Android/data/com.dotemu.titanquest/files/Preferences/Settings", or reinstall the game.

Thank you for your understanding.

Everything is great with the game and runs well on nvidia  shield tablet, but 2 problems that take a star a way for each problem I have with the game. Firstly no Immortal Throne expansion and no multi player which is disappointing.

The game was originally a great action RPG, probably one of the best ever made, but this port lacks a few key things: 1- no multi-player, 2- doesn't contain the expansion (immortal throne) which, IIRC, had key features, such as a stash, and 3- the controls aren't quite good enough to prevent you from dying once in a while. Good effort on the slowdown effect and auto-potion, but sometimes, your character just doesn't move out of a mob or is picking an item instead of attacking. 4- the UI on a Pixel C is HUGE

My first issue is that lack of customizable controls (hard to manage). Also, tip (rather, "Warning,") for Nexus 6 users. The only way to get a halfway decent framerate is to: install a custom kernel that force-manages thermal throttle (blu_spark r50 is the only one I've found that actually does this), install a kernel manager like Kernel Adiutor, set the throttle limit high, and max out all your cores and gpu. The Nexus 6 CAN handle it, but only barely (maybe 30-35 fps), and only if pushed to the limit.
Galaxy S6: No slow down or bad frame rate, no need for low graphics. Works perfectly. Loved it then; love it now!
